    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-05-03T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-05-03T02:00:00-05:00" n="372"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d372">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/2203: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morris</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-05-03T16:00:00+09:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 3, 1919, 4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received May 3, 12.47 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your February 21, 4 p.m.<note n="90" xml:id="d372fn90">See footnote 74, <ref
                            target="#pg_424">p. 424</ref>.</note> The Minister for Foreign Affairs
                    has handed me the following note:<note n="91" xml:id="d372fn91">The original
                        text of the memorandum is in Japanese; the English text is a translation
                        received by the Department from the American Embassy in Tokyo.</note>
                    <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“In accordance with the statement in the Foreign Office’s memorandum of
                            the 2d April, which was a reply to the American Ambassador’s memorandum
                            of March 11, 1919, in regard to a new loan consortium in China, the
                            Governments of Great Britain and France were consulted. The Imperial
                            Government in order to settle the embarrassing and complex questions
                            which may arise in the operation of the scheme has decided to approve of
                            the official notes [<hi rend="italic">suggestion</hi>] set forth in the
                            Ambassador’s memorandum of letting the banking groups exchange views,
                            subject to the approval of their respective Governments. The Imperial
                            Government therefore will issue the necessary instructions to its
                            interested bankers.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Morris</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
